docs.text: to make a film about gambling , a filmmaker will usually have to play up the glamorous side to get the audience behind the characters .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: this is because few moviegoers will care a whole lot about some guy in a leisure suit or terry cloth shirt sitting at a folding card table with a stogie in his mouth .

docs.text: rounders , however , seems to go more for the latter than the former .

docs.text: the card clubs mike and worm frequent aren't very glamorous at all .

docs.text: there's a basement , a lodge with elk heads on the wall , a goulash joint - these are the kinds of locales in which director john dahl sets his shots .

docs.text: except for one brief instance when the two players visit atlantic city , the film is bereft of the flashing lights of the casinos or the pleasant color of the green felt table .

docs.text: the reason rounders still captures our attention is because it is less about the game of poker than it is about the personalities which enjoy and are slaves to it .

docs.text: matt damon is very natural as mike , who struggles between his desire to play the straight and narrow by finishing law school , and answering what may be his true calling , playing professional poker .

docs.text: john turturro , who amazes me with his acting range , tones it down in this film by playing joey knish , a virtual poker prodigy in his time who now plays the underground games to make rent and child support payments .
